*God. God. God,* Polaris repeated in his head, the situation still not having dawned on him yet. He was usually so focused so... able to just *fix* things. He never faltered, but now? His mind was TV static. As he reached the lake, he knew Malachite wouldnt be too far behind. His stand has the longest range Polaris knows of but that was when searching the ground. There were trees surrounding the lake, and Polaris grabbed a thick branch of one with Star Platinum, swinging himself up to the top of the tree and hiding in the cluttered leaves.

He takes a deep breath.
"...Polaris?"
He heard him, but stayed silent.

"Polaris, please,"
He listens closely, still examining the ground passively.
"I can find you, but I want you to come out on your own. Please?"
Polaris refused. He focused himself on his ability sleep was still clinging at him, but if he could just focus enough energy, he could get the *hell* out of there to grab a moment to think.

He needs time to creep up on Polaris, in case he tries to run off again.
"You're tired. We both know if you use your ability you'll be incapacitated, and if you don't use it I'll find you. I just want to talk."

*No. I need time to think.*
He stayed quiet still, knowing this wasnt going to end well, but being too.. *distracted* to care.

"If you need time, I'll give it to you,"
Malachite has him. Tentacles swirl tentatively around the cluster of trees Polaris must've jumped into.
"Just *stop running.* I'll give you time, but we need to talk at some point."

*Shit,* Polaris thought to himself, not having realized Malachite could easily find where he is. He thought itd take at least *some* time, not 5 seconds. *Thats what I get for underestimating the strongest person I know...* he thought to himself with a low, frustrated grumble.

*Come on focus, focus,* focus. *Where should I where can I land where nobody can find me. The warp portal? No, last time I went through the portal... The pizzeria? Maybe he could convince Solus to let him hide there and just process stuff... no, Solus wouldnt approve, probably.. god. This sucks.*

"Polaris..."
Shit. Polaris can't use his ability now, he'll either fall out of the tree (bad) or manage to teleport and then immediately faint (worse).
"Just... come out. Please. We need to talk."
..Whats there to talk about? he says, barely above a whisper, part of him hoping Malachite heard, part of him hoping he didnt.

Malachite picks up on the soft noise.
"Hmm?"
He softens his voice, like he's calling a wild animal.
"I didn't quite catch that. Can you come closer please?"

Polaris.. didnt want to come down. He felt immature like a child whose parent was calling them down only to punish them. He let himself sit down, putting his back to the tree, and he sighed. ...Why should I?
"Because I want to talk. I'm not angry, Polaris."

Yeah? And whats there to talk about? he arches his brow not like itll do anything. Malachite cant fucking see him. How the people who are practically my family are throwing a revolution over the people who *raised me?*
"It's a subject we need to discuss. Can you come down here?"
...No. *I dont want you to see my face.* We can talk from here.
"...Alright, that works."
Malachite withdraws his tentacles, leaving a few beneath the tree in case Polaris tries to do something stupid.
Sensing less of Hierophant on the tree, he loosens up a little. He didnt exactly *like* being tied up by Hierophant.. Either way, if Malachite wanted to talk, Polaris wasnt going to start it up.

"...Are you ready to talk?"
Malachite glances up at the tree before sitting on the ground, cross-legged. He shivers.
...Ill let you take the lead.

"Alright."
He sighs. *This is... a lot to explain.*
"Polaris, you know me. I wouldn't do something like this without thinking, right?"
*You do a lot without thinking,* he thinks with an amused huff, but he hums, biting back his tongue. Yeah. I know.
"I've thought about this... a lot. This isn't a spur-of-the-moment decision. I really do think this is the best course of action."
He frowned. The Plasma did nothing wrong... and in the end, theyre more powerful than any of the muns. If Malachite really thought about this, hed realize that...
"To be frank, the missions the Plasma give us *don't make sense.* This system as a whole doesn't make any sense. If they're trying to save worlds, why are there reapers?"
*To gather energy to keep the Void running...* he thought to himself with another huff. Didnt he tell Malachite this already?
"Don't worlds already die without meddling? Why would they need to change the numbers artificially?"
Because that isnt enough for the void. Not even half of us would have power if we left it alone.
"Why?"
Why what?
"Why is it different? And how does the Plasma know about it? For that matter, why do they *care?"*

*Why is what different?* he asked himself, too tired to figure out what Malachite meant. So, he just answers the last question. Why would a king look for power for his people? Its a system, Mala. They do it because were like their citizens. I guess.
"So why don't we use another energy source? Humans use water or nuclear power."
Void power is different.
"How?"
Well. For one, we power ourselves on the *remains of a dead world.* Humans use resources like water, wind, whatever we use *dead worlds.* I dont think theres a substitute for that.
"How do they translate that into usable energy?"
//humans use resources like earth, wind and fire
Fuck, I dont *know,* Malachite! he shouted leaning over the side of the branch and peering over the side to glare at Malachite. Ask the people who take care of that shit!

"No fault of your own, Polaris. People get angry. It doesn't matter, really." Morise tilts their head. "Would you like to stay at the Plasma Zone for a while? None of the mun townsfolk are particularly... organized, really. They need some time to settle down, and while that's happening, I believe you'd do better staying away, for a little while. Keeping all this up is putting a huge weight on your shoulders." Morise puts on a.... 'sympathetic' tone.

Polaris turned to Morise, opening his mouth before realizing he didnt know how to respond, shutting his teeth with a small *clink* and facing the lake again. Something about Morises choice of words felt... *degrading.* Disorganized? The *muns?* There may be a few dumbasses, but these people are some of the most organized people Polaris knows, having practically built their own civilization with low crime and high hopes. But the more Polaris pondered on this, the more tired he became. He really had stretched himself out, huh?
...Lemme sleep on it, he slurs tiredly, resting his head sideways on his knees and closing his eyes, letting the sound of the wind blowing lead him to sleep without a second thought.
"Okay." Morise sits down, cross-legged, and thinks about how they can work with this.

Polaris wakes up with a jolt. Not an unusual occurrence, probably another stupid nightmare. Though he still didnt feel at all rested, he felt more... lucid. He could see a bit more clearly. No. Its enough, though, he mumbles, yawning into his hand and sitting normally now instead of having his knees hugged to his chest. What was the question again..?
"More of a proposal. Stay in the Plasma Zone for a little while and recuperate." Morise doesn't even twitch, still sitting cross-legged.

I saw how they acted in the group chat.. they probably didnt want me to even know about this at all-* any *of this. God. Fuck.*
